{{Infobox ethnic group
|group=Greeks in Poland
|population=3600 <ref>http://www.stat.gov.pl/cps/rde/xbcr/gus/LUD_ludnosc_stan_str_dem_spo_NSP2011.pdf</ref> 
|popplace=[[Wrocław]], [[Police, West Pomeranian Voivodeship|Police]] i [[Zgorzelec]], [[Świdnica]], [[Ustrzyki Dolne]] and [[Bielawa]].{{citation needed|date=April 2009}}
|related-c=[[Greek diaspora]]
}}
'''Greeks in Poland''' form one of the country's smaller [[Ethnic minorities in Poland|minority groups]].

==History==
[[File:Cerkiew w Zgorzelcu-2.jpg|left|thumb|180px|The Orthodox Church of Ss. Helen and Constantine along Lubańska Street in [[Zgorzelec]] was built in large part thanks to the support of the local Greek community.]]Greeks, particularly merchants and traders have been present in the Polish lands since the [[Middle Ages]], funding a number of [[Eastern Orthodox church architecture|Orthodox churches]] throughout the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]]. However most of these immigrants eventually assimilated into the diverse groups that trace their heritage from this polity such as [[Poles]], [[Lithuanians]], [[Belarusians]], and [[Ukrainians]].<ref>Topolski Jerzy (red) Dzieje Poznania, tom I cz. 1 do roku 1793, Warszawa-Poznań 1988, Państwowe Wydawnictwo Naukowe {{ISBN|83-01-08195-3}}</ref>

Most self-identified Greeks in Poland today trace their heritage to the large number of Greek citizens who fled [[Refugees of the Greek Civil War#Poland|as refugees]] from the [[Greek Civil War]] and were admitted into Poland.
<ref name="NYT">{{citation|title=Ousted Greek Red on a Polish Visit: Markos, who led guerillas in Civil War, was believed dead or in prison; 10,000 Greeks in Poland|periodical=The New York Times|last=Gruson|first=Sydney|date=1957-02-07|accessdate=2009-04-27|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0612FD3C5F147B93C5A91789D85F438585F9}}</ref> They consisted largely of former partisan units from the [[Macedonia (Greece)|Macedonia region of Greece]].

Most had been farmers before their flight from Greece.<ref name="Fleming">{{citation|title=Greek 'Heroes' in the Polish People's Republic and the Geopolitics of the Cold War, 1948-1956|first=Michael|last=Fleming|doi=10.1080/00905990802080596|journal=Nationalities Papers|volume=36|issue=3|date=July 2008|pages=375–397}}</ref> In total, from 1949 to 1951, 12,300 people from Greece came to Poland, of whom roughly one-quarter were children.<ref name="Wojecki1999">{{citation|first=Mieczysław|last=Wojecki|journal=Zakorzenienie|volume=4|issue=6|year=1999|url=http://zakorzenianie.most.org.pl/za6/02.htm|title=Przemiany demograficzne społeczności greckiej na Ziemi Lubuskiej w latach 1953-1998/Demographics of the Greek community in Lubusz Land in the years 1953-1998|accessdate=2009-04-09}}</ref>

Most refugees arrived by sea through the port at [[Gdynia]]. The Polish government chose to settle them in the territories west of the [[Oder River]] near the border with [[East Germany]], especially near [[Zgorzelec]].<ref name="Wojecki1999"/> About 200 were also sent to [[Krościenko, Bieszczady County|Krościenko]] in the southeast, near the [[Bieszczady Mountains]] in a formerly ethnic Ukrainian area.<ref>{{citation|title=From Gramos Mountain towards Lower Schleszia: Refugees from the Greek Civil War in Eastern Europe and Central Asia|journal=New Balkan Politics|volume=7/8|last=Troebst|first=Stefan|url=http://newbalkanpolitics.org.mk/napis.asp?id=19&lang=English|year=2003|accessdate=2009-04-27|issn=1409-8709}}</ref> Initially, the refugees were celebrated as anti-capitalist heroes and given significant government assistance in building new lives and integrating in Poland.<ref name="Fleming"/> Initially, they found employment on farms, for which they were well suited because of their rural background; however, they later gravitated towards urban areas.<ref name="Wojecki1999"/>

Some refugees chose to return to Greece early on.<ref name="Wojecki1999"/> By 1957, still roughly 10,000 remained in Poland.<ref name="NYT"/> However, suspicions later fell on them of being [[Titoism|Titoist]] agents. A large number were deported to Bulgaria in 1961.<ref name="RFE">{{citation|publisher=Radio Free Europe Evaluation and Analysis Department|title=Yugoslavs protesting against alleged deportations of Macedonians from Poland to Bulgaria|series=Yugoslav Special|volume=1059/1061|date=1961-05-30|accessdate=2009-04-27|url=http://www.osaarchivum.org/files/holdings/300/8/3/text/5-5-139.shtml|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226110217/http://www.osaarchivum.org/files/holdings/300/8/3/text/5-5-139.shtml|archivedate=2012-02-26|df=}}</ref>
After a 1985 agreement between the governments of Poland and Greece that enabled Greek refugees to receive retirement pensions at home, the number of Greeks in Poland has deteriorated further.<ref>
{{Citation
|url=http://www.greece.pl/polski/grecypol.htm
|title=Ambasada Grecji w Warszawie - Grecy w Polsce
|publisher=www.greece.pl
|accessdate=2009-06-09
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

The refugees belonged to different ethnicities, including half reportedly of [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian ethnicity]] and speaking the [[Macedonian language]].<ref name="RFE"/> Two Polish experts in Minority Studies, Alfred F. Majewicz and Tomasz Wicherkiewicz, claim that the Polish government cooperated with Greek refugees in forcing Macedonian refugees to adopt Hellenic names, and prevented them from opening their own schools and organisations.<ref>{{Citation|last=Majewicz|first=Alfred F. |author2=Wicherkiewicz, Tomasz|year=1998|title=Minority Rights Abuse in Communist Poland and Inherited Issues|journal=[[Acta Slavica Iaponica]]|publisher=Slavic Research Center|volume=16|location=[[Sapporo]] (Japan)|url=http://src-h.slav.hokudai.ac.jp/publictn/acta/16/alfred/alfred.html}}</ref>

In 1950 the refugees from Greece were organized in the Community of Political Refugees from Greece ({{lang-pl|Gmina Demokratycznych Uchodźców Politycznych z Grecji}}), based in [[Zgorzelec]]. Two years later it moved to [[Wroclaw]] and was renamed in 1953 [[Nikos Beloyannis]] Union of Political Refugees from Greece ({{lang-pl|Związek Uchodźców Politycznych z Grecji im. Nikosa Belojanisa}}).<ref>{{lang-pl|[http://grecy.eu.interia.pl/pliki/art4/art4.html Odysseas Association of Greeks in Poland]}}</ref><ref name="simoncini">{{Citation|last=Simoncini|first=Gabriele|year=1998|title=National Minorities of Poland at the end of the Twentieth Century|journal=The Polish Review|volume=XLIII|issue=2|pages=11–33|url=http://www.gabrielesimoncini.it/Publications/Docs/National%20Minorities%20PR.rtf|accessdate=2010-03-18|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722033735/http://www.gabrielesimoncini.it/Publications/Docs/National%20Minorities%20PR.rtf|archivedate=2011-07-22|df=}}</ref> After the fall of the dictatorship in Greece it changed its name into Association of Greeks in Poland ({{lang-pl|Towarzystwo Greków w Polsce}}), but in 1989, an internal schism led to the creation of the Association of Macedonians in Poland ({{lang-pl|Stowarzyszenie Macedończyków w Polsce}}).<ref name="simoncini"/>

==Minority status==
In his essay, published by the ''Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights'', professor Slawomir Lodzinski states:
<blockquote>
At present, the full legal protection is limited to this national minorities which are groups of Polish citizens, are “old”, “native” and on non-immigrant origin. This perspective has caused that the groups of Greeks and Macedonians who have been recognized as national minorities from the 1950s, from the beginning of the 1990s are not treated as national minorities by the state.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.minelres.lv/reports/poland/poland_NGO.htm|title=The protection of national minorities in Poland|last=Lodzinski|first=Slawomir|date=September 1999|publisher=Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights|accessdate=16 January 2010|location=Warsaw}}</ref>
</blockquote>

Answering a question by [[Brunon Synak]], President of the [[Kashubian-Pomeranian Association]], at a meeting organized by the [[Council of Europe]] in 2002, Mr. Dobiesław Rzemieniewski, Head of the National Minorities Division in the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Administration, explained that Greeks and Macedonians are "not classified as national minorities since they do not meet the requirement of being traditionally domiciled on the territory of the Republic of Poland".<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/minorities/3_FCNMdocs/PDF_1st_SR_Poland_Annexes_en.pdf|title=Minutes of the meeting with representatives of national and ethnic minorities concerning  the Report to the Secretary General of the Council of Europe on the Realisation by the Republic of Poland of the Provisions of the Framework Convention of the Council of Europe for the Protection of National Minorities|date=September 3, 2002|publisher=[[Council of Europe]]|accessdate=16 January 2010|location=Warsaw}}</ref>

