{{Infobox language family |name=High Franconian |altname= Oberfränkisch |region=[[Bavaria]], [[Baden-Württemberg]], [[Thuringia]], [[Saxony]] |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] |fam3=[[West Germanic languages|West]] |fam4=[[High German languages]] |child1=[[East Franconian German|East Franconian]] |child2=[[South Franconian German|South Franconian]] |glotto=high1287 |glottorefname=High Franconian |map=Oberdeutsche Mundarten.png |mapcaption=Upper German languages, with High Franconian in red and purple {{Legend|#EE3B3B|1: [[East Franconian German|East Franconian]]}} {{Legend|#8B1C62|2: [[South Franconian German|South Franconian]]}} }}
'''High Franconian''' ({{lang-de|oberfränkische Dialekte}}) is a part of [[High German languages|High German]] consisting of [[East Franconian German|East Franconian]] and [[South Franconian German|South Franconian]].<ref>Noble, Cecil A. M. (1983). ''Modern German dialects'' New York [u.a.], Lang, p. 119</ref> Because of fundamental differences in structure, it is factually not justified.<ref>Glück, Helmut (ed.). ''Metzler-Lexikon Sprache''. Metzler, 1993, p. 442. </ref>
It is part of the [[Franconian languages]] area, spoken southeast of the [[Rhine Franconian]] area.
It is spoken in [[Germany]] around [[Karlsruhe]], [[Erlangen]], [[Fürth]], [[Heilbronn]] and [[Würzburg]] and a small area in [[France]]. It is disputed whether [[Nuremberg]] in Germany belongs to its area. Surnames from the area of High Franconian include [[Bauer (surname)|Bauer]], [[Hofmann]], [[Merkel (surname)|Merkel]], [[Paulus (surname)|Paulus]], [[Schmidt (surname)|Schmidt]] and [[Schneider (surname)|Schneider]].
High Franconian is transitional between [[Upper German]] and [[Central German]] with similarity to [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]]. It is sometimes considered part of [[Central German]], or part of neither Upper nor Central German.
