{{Other uses}}
[[File:BattleofSluys.jpeg|thumb|Melee aboard ships at the [[Battle of Sluys]] 1340 (BNF Fr. 2643, 15th century)]]
[[File:Battle of Lutzen.jpg|thumb|''[[Battle of Lutzen (1632)|Battle of Lützen]]'' by  [[Carl Wahlbom]] depicting a melee in which King [[Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden]] was killed on 16 November 1632.]]
'''Melee''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|m|eɪ|l|eɪ}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|m|ɛ|l|eɪ}}, French: '''mêlée''' {{IPA-fr|mɛle|}}) or '''pell-mell''' battle  generally refers to disorganized [[close combat]] in battles fought at abnormally close range with little central control once it starts.{{sfn|OED|2015}}

In the 1579 translation of [[Plutarch]]'s ''Lives of the noble Grecians and Romanes'', [[Sir Thomas North]] uses the term 'pelmel' to refer to a disorganized retreat.<ref name="phrases">https://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/pell-mell.html</ref> The phrase was later used in its current spelling in [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'', 1594:

{{Quote
|text= "March on, ioine brauelie, let vs to it pell mell, If not to heauen then hand in hand to hell."
}}

The phrase comes from the French expression ''pêle-mêle'', a rhyme based on the old French ''mesler'', meaning to mix or mingle. 
<ref name="phrases" /><ref>https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/pell-mell</ref>

The French term ''melee'' was first used in English in c. 1640 (also derived from the old French ''mesler'',<ref>https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/melee#English</ref>  but the Old French stem survives in ''[[:wikt:medley|medley]]'' and ''[[:wikt:meddle|meddle]]'').{{sfn|OED|2015}}

In military aviation, a melee has been described as "[a]n air battle in which several aircraft, both friend and foe, are confusingly intermingled".{{sfn|Kumar|DeRemer|Marshall|2004|p=462}}

[[Lord Nelson]] described his tactics for the [[Battle of Trafalgar]] as inducing a "pell mell battle" focused on engagements between individual ships where the superior morale and skill of the [[Royal Navy]] would prevail.{{sfn|Fremont-Barnes|2005|p=38}}

The [[destroyer]] night action of the second [[Naval Battle of Guadalcanal]] on 13 November 1942, was so utterly chaotic and the ships were so intermingled that an officer on {{USS|Monssen|DD-436|6}} later likened it to "a barroom brawl after the lights had been shot out".<ref name="guadalcanal441">Frank, ''Guadalcanal'', p. 441.</ref>

