The '''Tanoli''' ([[Hindko language|Hindko]]/{{lang-ur|تنولی}}, تناولی; {{lang-hin|تنولي}}) are a tribe living mostly in the Hazara area of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name="Soldier Sahibs">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R6mLH_rImHYC&pg=PT96&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGu4CI873eAhXSYlAKHWzRCREQuwUILjAA#v=onepage&f=false |title=Soldier Sahibs: The Men Who Made the North-West Frontier |first=Charles |last=Allen |publisher=Hachette |year=2012 |page=96}}</ref> They form the majority of the population of [[Lassan Nawab]] union council.<ref> {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CoowAAAAYAAJ&q=Tanoli&dq=Tanoli&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAs5mC7r3eAhVB66QKHcGMDdY4ChDoAQg8MAM |title=Initiating Devolution for Service Delivery in Pakistan: Ignoring the Power Structure |first1=Shahrukh Rafi |last1=Khan |first2=Foqia Sadiq |last2=Khan |first3=Aasim Sajjad |last3=Akhtar |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2007 |page=129}}</ref> The Tanoli describe themselves either as Pashtuns from the [[Ghazni]] area or as [[Barlas]] Turks<ref>{{cite magazine|title=[[Herald (Pakistan)|Herald]] |page=101 |quote=The Tanolis' own history classifies them conflictingly as either Pakhtuns from the vicinity of Ghazni or Turks of the Barlas sub-clan. |volume=37 |issue=4—6 |year=2006}}</ref>but both the [[British India|British Indian colonial accounts]] and modern Pakistani scholars refute these hypotheses and claim they have probably indigenous origins.<ref>Hazara Gazeteer for 1883-1884, Lahore, 1884; pp 70-71; P. Mayne, Pashtun Border Tribes, London, 1956, p 54; Prof Dr [[Ahmad Hasan Dani]], History of the Northern Areas , Islamabad: National Institute for Historical and Cultural Research, 1989. pp 120-122</ref>  The Tanoli submitted to British colonial  rule in the 1840s.<ref name="Soldier Sahibs" />

